insert into JournalArticle (id_, resourcePrimKey, groupId, companyId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, articleId, version, title, description, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired, indexable) values (3913, 3914, 14, 1, 2, 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '2860', 1.0, 'Stories-NEISGEI', '', '<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n\n<root default-locale=\"en_US\" available-locales=\"en_US\">\n	<dynamic-element name=\"company-image\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1687\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1645&amp;t=1201073156563</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"company-link\" type=\"text\">\n		<dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.neisgei.org]]></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"company-link-name\" type=\"text\">\n		<dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.neisgei.org]]></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"quote\" type=\"text_area\">\n		<dynamic-content language-id=\"en_US\"><![CDATA[<p><em><font size=\"3\">&ldquo;After reviewing a number of other options, we believe Liferay remains the leading portal solution out there. Its dedication to open standards is a key factor in using the Liferay portal for community driven air quality work.&rdquo; </font></em></p><p align=\"right\">&ndash; Stefan Falke, Research Professor of Energy, Environmental and Chemical Engineering at Washington University in St. Louis</p>]]></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"content\" type=\"text_area\">\n		<dynamic-content language-id=\"en_US\"><![CDATA[<h2>Company Profile</h2> <p>The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and Washington University in St. Louis are working toward realizing the vision of the Networked Environmental Information System for Global Emissions Inventories initiative (NEISGEI &ndash; pronounced &lsquo;niceguy&rsquo;) with the goal of applying the latest information science and technologies to open web access of disparate emissions data and analysis tools.</p> <h2>Challenge</h2> <p>In order to foster research, analysis and decision-making NEISGEI needed a framework for networking global air emissions inventories in a way that fostered aggregation and integration of the separate content inventories provided by the many participating groups of the air quality community. Accordingly, the EPA sought a solution that included a web portal and tasked the CAPITA team at Washington University in St. Louis with developing an appropriate platform.</p> <p>As CAPITA had a long history of working with portals as a means of promoting open discussion, the concept of virtual community was very familiar to them. They, in fact, keenly monitored the standards for portal interoperability, so the ability to share content with other portals was a key factor in the selection process. Other portal requirements included a catalog of distributed emission inventory data, tools for processing and analyzing the data, means for registering new data and tools, and an environment for collaboration among international research groups and policy-makers.</p> <p>After reviewing a number of commercial and open source products, the CAPITA team chose to develop its community air emissions portal using Liferay because of its commitment to interoperability and open standards. Liferay was also chosen for its ease of customization, which aligned with the NEISGEI vision for a truly collaborative and community-based sharing environment.</p> <h2>Solution</h2> <p>Leveraging Liferay Portal\'s functionality and its dedication to open standards, the CAPITA team created the NEISGEI web portal through which emissions data and visualization/analysis tools can now be accessed. While the initial users came primarily from the scientific community and those involved with air quality management and policy development, the community is open to the public at large as an educational resource for anyone interested.</p> <p>With the new portal solution, the EPA and the Air Quality community is able to facilitate better communication, sharing and learning, which ultimately results in more effective policy development. In the portal environment users can contribute their own content and provide feedback on the scientific objectives of the collective using Liferay\'s out of the box collaboration tools such as message boards, mail, blogs and a centralized document library, among others. Web tools and applications enabling data access, visualization and analysis have also been provided.</p> <p>With support from Liferay, further portlet interoperability features were introduced and will continue to develop. Leveraging Liferay&rsquo;s compliance with JSR-170 industry standards, the NEISGEI portal will be able to exchange information between portlets within the portal itself as well as between the many disparate portal applications used by the air quality community. This, along with data integration, continues to be an area of greater vision and development. Said Stefan Falke, Research Professor of Energy, Environmental and Chemical Engineering at Washington University and CAPITA&rsquo;s NEISGEI project lead: &quot;With its dedication to open standards and interoperability, Liferay will serve us for years to come.&quot;</p> <p><em>Disclaimer: Liferay is not endorsed or sponsored&nbsp; by Washington University in St. Louis or the US Environmental Protection Agency and the opinions expressed in this case study are not necessarily those of the University or the Agency.</em></p>]]></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image1\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1688\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1688&amp;t=1201073156576</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image1\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1689\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1646&amp;t=1201073156578</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image2\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1690\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1690&amp;t=1201073156581</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image2\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1691\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1647&amp;t=1201073156583</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image3\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1692\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1692&amp;t=1201073156586</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image3\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1693\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1648&amp;t=1201073156589</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image4\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1694\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1694&amp;t=1201073156592</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image4\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1695\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1649&amp;t=1201073156595</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image5\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1696\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1696&amp;t=1201073156598</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image5\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1697\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1650&amp;t=1201073156601</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image6\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image6\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image7\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image7\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image8\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image8\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image9\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image9\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n</root>', 'general', 'SHOWCASE', 'SHOWCASE', SPECIFIC_TIMESTAMP_20070801194700, TRUE, 2, 'Joe Bloggs', FALSE, TRUE);
insert into JournalArticle (id_, resourcePrimKey, groupId, companyId, userId, userName, createDate, modifiedDate, articleId, version, title, description, content, type_, structureId, templateId, displayDate, approved, approvedByUserId, approvedByUserName, expired, indexable) values (3915, 3916, 14, 1, 2, 'Joe Bloggs', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, '2863', 1.0, 'Stories-Oakwood', '', '<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n\n<root default-locale=\"en_US\" available-locales=\"en_US\">\n	<dynamic-element name=\"company-image\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1917\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1804&amp;t=1201073923739</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"company-link\" type=\"text\">\n		<dynamic-content><![CDATA[http://www.oakwood.com]]></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"company-link-name\" type=\"text\">\n		<dynamic-content><![CDATA[www.oakwood.com]]></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"quote\" type=\"text_area\">\n		<dynamic-content language-id=\"en_US\"><![CDATA[<p><em><font size=\"3\">&quot;Our view is that a portal is fundamentally an application integration tool rather than a solution in and of itself, so we were intent on applying our program costs to rapid customization, not license fees. This turned out to be the right mindset because within a month of initial rollout, our Liferay-based customer portal helped us edge out competitors in several hard-won contracts. Sales people actually started calling HQ to thank the development team.&quot; </font></em></p> <p align=\"right\">&nbsp;</p><p align=\"right\">- Eric Nathanson, Oakwood</p>]]></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"content\" type=\"text_area\">\n		<dynamic-content language-id=\"en_US\"><![CDATA[<h2>Company Profile</h2> <p>Oakwood Worldwide is the largest temporary housing provider worldwide. With 40 years of multi-family housing experience and 30 years of industry leadership in corporate housing, Oakwood Worldwide is the most experienced leader in temporary furnished apartments. With access to over 400,000 apartments in more than 2,000 U.S. cities, as well as select locations in Canada, Asia, and Europe, 85% of Fortune 500 firms depend on Oakwood Worldwide.</p> <h2>Challenge</h2> <p>To maintain a competitive edge over other housing providers, Oakwood\'s management recognized the need to upgrade their disparate legacy systems. By implementing a more efficient and cost-effective process model, Oakwood hoped to increase profitability and improve the customer\'s ability to book and schedule reservations. With over 400,000 apartments all across the world, Oakwood needed an application that would not only query all availabilities that matched a customer\'s criteria, but&nbsp;would also allow sales agents to effectively meet those requests.</p> <p>Oakwood needed the following from an application:</p> <ul> <li>A Profiles System that would allow sales agents to easily update the properties they are responsible for.</li> <li>Content Management System that would manage the layout and content of the website.</li> <li>A website with a new look and feel that would improve the customer\'s ability to search and book apartments.</li> </ul> <h2>Resolution</h2> <p>Oakwood Worldwide selected Liferay and its enterprise portal to implement the functionality it needed. By leveraging Liferay Portal Enterprise\'s framework, Liferay implemented the following:</p> <ul> <li><strong>Profiles Portlet</strong> - Liferay helped build a Profiles portlet that allowed sales agents to manage properties they were responsible for. This included the ability to upload property images, descriptions, and other information that would help a sales agent in closing a sale.</li> <li><strong>XSLT CMS</strong> - Oakwood\'s website is driven by Liferay\'s Content Management System. Via an XSLT templating system, Oakwood can control the content displayed on the site along with its layout.</li> <li><strong>eInvoicing</strong> - Liferay used web services to integrate a .NET invoicing system into its own portlet within Liferay Portal.</li> </ul> <p>As opposed to spending hundreds of thousands of dollars for a commercial application\'s license alone, Oakwood Worldwide saw the advantage of using Liferay\'s open source software to cut costs and build a well architected, long-term solution.</p>]]></dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image1\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1918\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1918&amp;t=1201073923751</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image1\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1919\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1805&amp;t=1201073923754</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image2\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1920\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1920&amp;t=1201073923757</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image2\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1921\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1806&amp;t=1201073923760</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image3\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1922\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1922&amp;t=1201073923763</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image3\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1923\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1807&amp;t=1201073923767</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image4\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1924\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1924&amp;t=1201073923770</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"thumb-image4\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content id=\"1925\">/image/journal/article?img_id=1808&amp;t=1201073923774</dynamic-content>\n	</dynamic-element>\n	<dynamic-element name=\"full-image5\" type=\"image\">\n		<dynamic-content></